			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Efficient Demand Evaluation of Fixed-Point Attributes using Static Analysis</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/IdrissRiouak.html">Idriss Riouak</a>, <a href="../profile/NiklasFors.html">Niklas Fors</a>, <a href="../profile/JesperÖqvist.html">Jesper Öqvist</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a>, <a href="../profile/ChristophReichenbach.html">Christoph Reichenbach</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695644">10.1145/3687997.3695644</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper contributes to attribute-grammar style meta-languages by improving evaluation of fixed-point attributes.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Fixed-point attributes are commonly used to express static analyses (e.g., dataflow) in language definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Its main goal is to reduce evaluation cost by using static analysis to avoid unnecessary recomputation.
</li></ul></li></ul>
